It is like discount starcraft. That is a compliment.

3 unit classes, changeable on the fly to 3 different variants. A single digit unit cap, with armies usually being between 2-4 units. No mining or building is available; the one resource is automatically generated. There is no tech or macro. No PvP - campaign only and no replayability offered. The campaign also only consists of pre-generated & triggered enemy unit spawns. It's rudimentary, but it offers some basic fun in it's short campaign. This is not something like StarCraft or C&C.

I come at this as a casual when it comes to RTS games; while Iron Marines comes with the flavor of the bigger names for PC, it is far more accessible. It runs at a nice pace for me, missions are replayable for those who like to grind their characters up before diving in, the controls are mostly intuitive...and all of this comes with iconic Ironhide art style that I grew to love in Kingdom Rush a couple of years ago. A big bonus for me is that you can swap out your units on the fly as needed to adjust your playstyle, yet you can only have so many. This is, however, taken into account as you can launch your hero back into orbit and drop them down again anywhere you have a vision radius up. About the only thing that I would critique is the movement and targeting system. Many of use growing up with RTS became used to micromanagement; the option of an attack move or, alternatively, double clicking an enemy to instruct nearby units to focus on it would do wonders (in my opinion) and make the higher difficulties a bit more fluid. All in all, this is quite a fun game and I don't intend to put it down any time soon!

I loved it. Think Halo meets the Kingdom Rush universe (and if you have not played Kingdom Rush then go RIGHT NOW). Two franchises that I personally adored! I love creating my bases, then sending a squad of Marines to kill a bunch of aliens. A few things which I think would be absolutely amazing: 1. Please, please, PLEASE add a Skirmish option so you can fight alien CPUs. 2. Custom map editors for said Skirmish. 3. Multiplayer? Nah. Instead, up the Skirmish and fight other Human or Alien CPUs! So, like a two to four battle, or maybe a three versus three? And lastly, or 4 (this is Skirmish related), I'd like to see teams. In fact, make some levels where you fight with/against other colonist humans! Ok, that's pretty lengthy. Maybe the longest review ever that I've written! Anyway, even if you don't think about my ideas, I just wanted to say, thank you for this! Keep updating! P.S could you make a wild-west Kingdom Rush style game?

An RTS fit for the small screen. For decades the Real-Time-Strategy genre was restricted to the PC and somewhat consoles. This isn't the first attempt to bring the genre to mobile devices, but it's certainly the first one to get it right. The controls are simple and easy to understand, I'm hoping this will be the foundation more mobile developers build upon for a genre that needs more attention and love. The story isn't much to delve into, but while it's there, it's just a reason to push towards the next mission. Graphically it lies on its own art style which works surprisingly well on the small screen. All units are unique in design and all buildings are easily recognisable after just two missions. I highly recommend this game to veterans of the RTS genre and new comers alike. This won't be a regrettable purchase and you will lose hours of time playing. 9/10

Updated Review: this game is still amazing as previous review stated, but I felt the new planet was a bit of a drag on higher difficulty, I felt the new heroes didn't add much and honestly are not viable pass casual however I must change my opinion on other heroes, blue steel (might be typing that wrong) is broken, she can rush missions and get places she shouldn't, her healing droids final upgrade doesn't work and her rail gun ability is op, the other two heroes are trash as one is required to be moved constantly for his benefits and the other bring extra squad support but doesn't do enough damage to justify bringing him over blue steel or the mercenary, speaking of which, the mercenary has the highest damage output in the game, he is viable for everything from long range damage to short range crowd control, he is the hero you need for Impossible, other then that I enjoyed this game it is amazing, and I question if they will bring another planet, as the end leaves off on a cliff hanger, oh! And the new upgrades are a bit meh but you really need them for better hold outs but the towers are too weak now to actually mean something, the laser tower is the best but It can't fight air and the other two can't do enough damage . content:
First of all, never did I expect someone would bring RTS to mobile, it's 
very new for me. I have always enjoyed playing RTS games, but I found the 
controls in this game are a bit dissatisfying. It lacks one of the most 
essential function, the attack move function. I would recommend to have a 
choice to switch between attack move , move and hold position. Maybe you 
could try putting the three buttons one the left side of the screen. It is 
also pretty hard to select units, especially of you want to select one of 
the units which are on top of or near to each other. I tried selecting the 
guardians to move forward but then I selected the others, resulting 
unwanted casualties. Maybe it just come hand in hand on the mobile 
platform. The other thing that bothered me is the formation. Melee units 
don't directly move forward when moving as a group but rather hid behind 
the ranged units, this made the melee units rather useless at most times. 
But overall, it is a very awesome game. I especially like and appreciate 
the art style, really love that cartoonish feeling. I can't wait for this 
game to come to the PC platform.
Lag crash

Overall this is a fun game that is tainted by charging for heroes and 
currency (used for special items to make levels easier). The campaign is 
short and the third planet has said "coming soon" for months. There are 
also a few grammatical issues which just look sloppy after being released 
for so long. The gameplay is enjoyable but I can't recommend purchasing the 
game since your hero choices will be very limited and more heroes are 
stupidly expensive and can only be purchased with real money. You also get 
ads in game for the currency and heroes talking about limited time offers 
and discounts which feels ridiculous after having to purchase the game. A 
premium game with freemium elements that negatively impact the experience. 
Update: Still no third world while a new Kingdom Rush game has been 
announced so I've moved this to two stars. Feels like false advertising.

Ironhide delivers yet again an amazing looking and well thought out game, but unfortunately (so far) it fails to give a challenge. It's entertaining, gorgeous, and conceptually brilliant. However, don't expect the same feeling of accomplishment or tactical challeneg you might have gotten from the Kingdom Rush series. The enemy feels a little flat on both planets, and the hero system feels a little recycled at this point (which is an almost unfair criticism given it's success in their other games). That being said the base building system is very unique and well executed! I'm excited to see where this game goes in the future or whatever game Ironhide puts out next!

This is Ironhide's best game yet. It is a pocket RTS, I love it. But I think it is more of a Dawn of War 3 than a StarCraft 2. And that is just fine with me. Yes, there are in app purchases, but you are given 3 heroes to start and they get points based on experience that level up their skills.  I was worried they would cheese up the game like a freemium and put ads or video ads for currency, but they haven't so far, and I'm about six missions in. I can't stand that stuff. I like a nice immersive experience. If you lose a mission you still get gold based on your effort, that's nice.  There is clever strategy here, cover and corners, advantage points, range and melee units and heroes. It's great so far and on normal it ain't easy.  I highly recommend this game.

content: Easy and honest review - its like an unofficial Starcraft Heroes. Humans with guns and mechs (Terran) ally with psychic aliens (Protoss) to battle a race of hideous mutants and bugs (Zerg). Squad combat simulation via tap and drag. Controls take some getting used to and its easy to accidentally send your troops headlong into enemy territory. Aside from that, graphics are smooth and vibrant; the music is good, fits the levels well and the character voices maintain the same charm as the other Ironhide games. Looking forward to new content for this game.

This is a pretty nice game. Lot of Halo and StarCraft parodies so that's fun. The style is simple and pretty easy to manage even with several squads running in different map areas. There's a couple odd spelling errors that take you out of it sometimes (campaign spelled as campaing) but that's about it for the problems I see. I would like to see the encyclopedia that Kingdom Rush had because I can't remember all of the enemy stats. I think it would be good to have the tower placement be up to us and not preset. It would also be nice to have the units be able to attack while moving because not all of them do (I understand the Sniper, that makes sense). Even without those bonuses, it's still an excellent addition to the Ironhide roster!

Excuse my language but F'ing AWESOME. First ironhide game I have played and going to buy the rest! You will not regret buying this. This game is challenging and actually quite immersive. Lots of upgrades and items to pummel your enemies to a pulp. There are in-game purchases that you can buy but they are not required to beat the game. Basically just different characters with different skills some better than others. You can also buy currency to buy items like mines and rockets which are also not needed just make some parts of the game easier. There is a huge upgrade tree where you can make your troops, structures, turrets, and squad leaders more powerful. Tons of achievements to gain and none are secret so you can mow down aliens for the sake of achievements and of course planet earth. I have purchased many games on the app store and this is by far the best money I have spent fun wise. Only downside is that some may say it lacks replayability but if you are a perfectionist or just enjoy the game like I do the 4 different difficulties and the toughness of the game will keep you occupied for quite some time. At least until you get your moneys worth. Ironhide I applaud you for making my Command and Conquor receptor tingle with joy and hope to see some updates and maybe new content. 5/5 will play more, will buy more.

I'm a huge fan of Iron Hide games; I got 100% on all three of their tower defense games. However, this game is a bit of a let down. It looks amazing, but the game play needs some love. It's difficult to select the units you want to, which almost always causes you to lose a few units at least. And sometimes the missions are not as fun as they are difficult, and it feels pointless. In Kindgom Rush, the challenge was fun.  I think Iron Marines could use a quick-tap icon of each unit on the field, or some other method of selecting a specific units quickly. If I have units I want to keep in the back, I have to choose between moving them individually, or moving all the units in a group and THEN selecting the one I want to move back, and most of the time you end up selecting the wrong unit while you're getting bomabarded. It REALLY takes me out of the game, and it's needlessly frustrating. This needs to be fixed before I can give this game more stars. I expect tighter controls from the makers of Kindgom Rush.

Excellent game, difficult and requires a lot of real strategy. Given the quality Kingdom Rush games, I hoped IronHide Studios would create a good RTS game. This game blew away all my expectations, setting a new precedent not just for mobile strategy games, but for all strategy games in general. It combines the excellent tower mechanics of kingdom rush with troop and resource management, requiring not just good defensive tower placement, but also well timed and planned offensive strikes to defeat enemies and complete your objectives. This game makes me think *really* hard, exercising my brain just as hard as a turn based game like Risk, while gracefully maintaining the realistic feal of RTS games. My only suggestion is that they improve the troop movement UI, as it's somewhat hard to quixkly manage lots of troops ar once. Other than that this game is excellent, and I hope Ironhide Studios can continue making these quality games!

Premium game that has ads, ingame currency IAP and starter bundles. C'mon. I know the ads and such are optional but the having those on an expensive premium game is just weird. As if the developers don't trust enough their product to make it fully F2P.  Speaking of which, game looks and sounds brilliant. It can also get quite difficult: there are some difficulty spikes and hard to read objectives at times that can ruin your game on first round. It can be quite frustrating.   But the level of detail is just something else. Thanks to all those intricate small details, replaying levels again don't feel as bad. You'll always discover something new. Loving it.   The game is somewhat difficult to control on a phone, especially the double tap to select all units sometimes does not work as expected.   I'd give the game higher score but the monetization scheme is simply too off-putting for me. I'd would have preferred a either premium and no ads, or fully f2p with trial paywall.
replyContent: Hi, in apps and ads are optional for those who want to get the credits. The game can be totally completed without using either of them.

This game is amazing. The gameplay and graphics are as fantastic as you would expect from the developers of the Kingdom Rush series. There is only one thing keeping this review from being 5 stars and that is the length of the campaign. I got so into the game that I finished the 24 missions in one day. This was disappointing. I know that I could go back and run through the game on the veteran and impossible modes and try to unlock every achievement, but I can't help feeling like the fun has ended when I just bought the game yesterday. I was also trying to find info on when the next planet is being released but I didn't see it anywhere. One thing that made the Kingdom Rush series so replayable was that every stage had two challenge modes with different conditions that had to be followed for victory, perhaps a similar strategy could be used to beef up the existing content?

As a huge fan of Ironhide's work and a mailing list subscriber pre-launch I was probably always going to love this game.   It does not disappoint.   As far as strategy games go, this is in the very top echelon in my opinion.  The design is beautiful, the balance and fairness is just right. You definitely, absolutely do not need to spend any more money than the initial asking price.   If you DO need to spend additional money, it is because you are either very curious about testing a new hero or because you are simply not good enough and require what I personally consider to be "bail-outs".   Ironhide has a unique ability to create strategy that is simple yet deep. There were numerous missions I failed very late only to be left considering all the possible alternate options I could have used to succeed.   Iron Marines rewards preparation and as the campaign progressed I found myself becoming particularly cautious about leaving my bases with only towers to defend them.   I truly have no negative feedback to give regarding the gameplay experience of this game. I have played on both mobile and tablet and surprisingly I prefer mobile as I can more easily use both thumbs to command units. On tablet I found myself using only my dominant index finger.   What I would love in future updates is a library of units and upgrades to log their statistics and brief descriptive copy. I do miss this as I really like perousing through the Kingdom Rush versions.   Overall, congratulations Ironhide. I thank you for delivering once again an extremely enjoyable and rewarding strategy experience.

There is also a major issue with in app purchases, there are simply not enough heroes, and being charged for one use items that are practically essential at times is annoying, the game should be skill based, not a grind to get items or a pay for a good hero. Really disappointed. I'm a huge fan of the Kingdom Rush series, having paid and beat them all 100%. I have waited patiently for this. This does not match the strategic precision of those titles unfortunately. Some levels of Kingdom Rush were decided by the slimmest of margins but always felt fair and perfectly balanced, leaving you with the just 'one more go' feel, certain that you knew what to do differently next time.  This game is much more woolly and loose in how you can do things, where you can place troops, when you can do things and generally level failure occurs with an overwhelming lack of consequence to one's strategic decisions. I think a lot of this is simply down to the move away from the rigid round based structure which has been sacrificed for the more open gameplay style. Unfortunately this decision means the game doesn't work anywhere near as well. It also lacks a clear tutorial.  It's a very pretty game with the usual high production values but the gameplay lets it down. I hope the developers go back to the drawing board and recapture the simplicity and beautiful clear structure of the Kingdom Rush titles, though I do enjoy the new Sci-Fi setting.

Whilst I would have blindly praised this master piece upon first buying it, I still would highly recommend this to fans and new comers alike. This game works brilliantly and it maintains the magnificent art style and units that whilst not as numerous or varied as the towers from its Kingdom Rush series, they are fresh and interesting functioning as should be expected from an RTS.   The features compared to those of the Kingdom Rush series lack in some areas that whilst not necessarily essential, show a slight lack of consideration. There is no encyclopedia that features buildings, units, and enemies telling of what they are or how they are best used. The hero leveling is greatly simplified compared to the previous, thought considering how many abilities the player can control it serves its purpose. There is no defense or skirmish feature to tie over after the campaign is completed, though they may add a endless waves mission eventually. There is a lack of air units available to the marines thought I imagine that they would be difficult to manage and program, along with interactions in certain levels.  All of these quibbles are mild nit-pick of the overall perfect package and it is early days and may be addressed in the future. Thought my complaints will probably not be resolved and these fact are annoying, I will continue to enjoy playing this game and hope that there are more planets planned other than the one teased to, along with another hero or two.  Keep being awesome Ironhide Studios.

Great Game, But... First things first. It is a Well executed game. Good strategy components with easy controls, beautiful artwork/ graphics and lots of fun.  My issue with this is simple. It's based on the principle that I as well as many other players looked forward to the release of this game and with how much the other premium heroes cost, it would be more fair to not charge the up front fee to play the game. I understand and respect the hard work that goes into making a game of this caliber, but I honesty can't see the price tag as justified.   Furthermore, there should be more ways within the game to provide the players incentives to earn more resources for research and weapons. Such as side quests, assault missions, sabotage missions or something along those lines. Why would anyone willingly watch ads? It's more of a rhetorical. I personally will avoid it.  All that aside this game remains a solid RTS with beautiful graphics and great depth. I look forward to updates and improvements if Ironhide may have some in store.

A truly amazing game and great feat for rts's on phones! It has all the action, strategy, goofy humor, and quirky art style we've come to expect from IronHide studios. Controls seem shallow at first, but have been truly optimized the best way it could be for an rts phone experience. The hardcore rts fans may find the challenge low, but doesn't take away from the fun of the over-all experience; however, there is a choice for different difficulties (with impossible diff. unlocking after the campaign). For those worried about IAP, IGNORE THE NEGATIVE NANCIES!! IAP's are done the same as any other IronHide game, nothing backhanded or sneaky here.  Everything is completely earnable in-game except for the extra heroes, which are definitely there for enjoyment purposes only and not needed to beat the game. In conclusion, I truly believe this to be one of the most enjoyable and highest quality phone games of 2017, so don't miss out!! See you all among the stars üòé

Wow all these salty reviews. People need to get their heads checked. This game is a true labour of love and in no way a P2W game. You can clear it without paying for any of the extras just like all their past Kingdom Rush games.   This is easily the best game I've ever played on Android. Better than most $20 indy trash on Steam I see popping up every other day. The touch controls are slick and responsive. The game runs at a buttery smooth fps and is actually optimized better than Kingdom Rush was. KR Origins had some laggy menus and loading but this game never hitches once.   I put in over 100 hours easily for KR, KR Frontier, and KR Origins. I'm super picky when it comes to giving a 5 star but Ironhide has blown me away yet again. This game exceeds my high expectations I had coming in and sets the bar for everyone else on what it means to be a paid app on the Play store. Bravo Ironhide, I tip my hat to you guys and hope all the best success so you can keep giving me games like this.
